WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:10.320 --> 00:00:12.450
Track and field takes New York,

00:00:12.450 --> 00:00:16.530
the fastest women on the planet,
a crowd to witness history,

00:00:16.530 --> 00:00:18.030
and a venture capitalist betting

00:00:18.030 --> 00:00:22.230
that women's sports have
achieved escape velocity.

00:00:28.110 --> 00:00:30.420
It's pretty incredible. So I get it.

00:00:30.420 --> 00:00:32.250
Like I get how this could be a thing.

00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:35.370
Can Alexis Ohanian, co-founder

00:00:35.370 --> 00:00:39.270
of Reddit prove his biggest
wins are still ahead?

00:00:39.270 --> 00:00:40.950
I look at Formula
One, the scale of that.

00:00:40.950 --> 00:00:41.970
It is an amazing business

00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:43.080
and it's humans going as fast

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:44.340
as possible from point A to point B.

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:46.680
In cars, in horses,
those are great sports.

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:48.600
These are humans just doing
it with their own legs.

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:50.550
And if we can't make
that as big of a story

00:00:50.550 --> 00:00:52.320
or even bigger, I, I

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:53.370
might as well find something else to do.

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:57.300
For two decades, Ohanian has
amassed a fortune betting on

00:00:57.300 --> 00:00:59.220
ideas others overlook.

00:00:59.220 --> 00:01:02.490
He co-founded Reddit when
social media was in its infancy,

00:01:02.490 --> 00:01:05.100
found success as an early stage investor

00:01:05.100 --> 00:01:07.770
and has helped launch the
recent boom in professional

00:01:07.770 --> 00:01:09.180
women's sports.

00:01:09.180 --> 00:01:11.340
But there've been hurdles along the way.

00:01:11.340 --> 00:01:13.500
There was a messy exit from Reddit,

00:01:13.500 --> 00:01:15.540
a venture partnership dissolved

00:01:15.540 --> 00:01:18.180
and a power struggle over a soccer team.

00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:20.670
All on top of the pressures of being Mr.

00:01:20.670 --> 00:01:22.110
Serena Williams

00:01:22.110 --> 00:01:25.080
and his determination to lean
into his role as the father

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:26.700
of two young girls.

00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:27.810
Do you get recognized?

00:01:29.190 --> 00:01:30.960
Nah, it depends on the context.

00:01:30.960 --> 00:01:34.650
It like in the Bay area,
more often, ironically just

00:01:34.650 --> 00:01:37.140
'cause of the whole tech
scene thing, you know,

00:01:37.140 --> 00:01:39.750
certainly there's still folks
who are like, Hey Reddit guy.

00:01:39.750 --> 00:01:41.070
There's obviously plenty
of folks who are like,

00:01:41.070 --> 00:01:42.420
Hey, Serena's husband.

00:01:42.420 --> 00:01:45.180
There's even a few who
are like Olympia's dad,

00:01:45.180 --> 00:01:46.230
which is is wonderful.

00:01:46.230 --> 00:01:47.910
It's also a little weird
'cause I'm like, she's eight,

00:01:47.910 --> 00:01:49.980
she hasn't done anything yet.

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:52.140
He's built a reputation
on Reddit nostalgia

00:01:52.140 --> 00:01:53.940
and tech idealism,

00:01:53.940 --> 00:01:56.790
but in the cutthroat worlds
of venture capital in sports.

00:01:56.790 --> 00:01:59.970
Is that enough to get
you over the finish line?

00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:01.410
Are you ready for your AMA

00:02:01.410 --> 00:02:02.410
Bring it?

00:02:02.410 --> 00:02:03.243
Yeah. Oh yeah.

00:02:03.243 --> 00:02:04.076
We are on our way uptown to meet Alexis.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:22.920
We're gonna start our
day at a sneaker store.

00:02:25.050 --> 00:02:29.130
All right, let's look for some shoes.

00:02:29.130 --> 00:02:30.720
All right. Hopefully the guest says 15.

00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:34.350
Are you really a size 15?
Yeah. Wait, let me see that.

00:02:34.350 --> 00:02:36.755
Are you, I'm not a size 15. Not

00:02:36.755 --> 00:02:37.920
in that neighborhood, huh.

00:02:37.920 --> 00:02:39.510
You need to pick out a
shoe. Don't you pick out

00:02:39.510 --> 00:02:40.890
shoes for special events?

00:02:40.890 --> 00:02:42.930
I do, I do. You did
the research. Yeah. Okay.

00:02:42.930 --> 00:02:45.060
If you look at the branding,
we have like a kind

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:48.660
of Athlos magenta, actually,
you know, this one's not bad,

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:50.670
so it might be a little too matchy

00:02:50.670 --> 00:02:51.721
matchy with the jacket. Match

00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:53.680
the outfit.

00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:54.513
Do you think outfit, I mean,
I'm not great on the colors.

00:02:54.513 --> 00:02:56.970
My wife's really good at the
color coordination thing.

00:02:56.970 --> 00:02:59.710
Before he married tennis
legend Serena Williams and

00:02:59.710 --> 00:03:03.340
before he co-founded Reddit,
Ohanian was a middle class kid

00:03:03.340 --> 00:03:04.690
with roots in Brooklyn.

00:03:05.590 --> 00:03:06.670
I managed to talk to my parents

00:03:06.670 --> 00:03:08.020
into getting me a computer.

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:10.720
It was a big investment and
then an internet connection.

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:12.910
And even though they had
no idea what I was doing on

00:03:12.910 --> 00:03:15.670
that computer, I found strangers
on the internet willing

00:03:15.670 --> 00:03:18.610
to help me with learning how to code and,

00:03:18.610 --> 00:03:20.590
and so that feeling that software provided

00:03:20.590 --> 00:03:23.740
and then the access to the
knowledge freely given by experts

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:26.440
to me, a dorky kid in my parents' house

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:27.970
was, was life changing.

00:03:27.970 --> 00:03:31.000
- Fast forward to Hanian
senior year at the University

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:32.140
of Virginia where he

00:03:32.140 --> 00:03:33.610
and his roommate Steve Huffman,

00:03:33.610 --> 00:03:37.150
pitched tech incubator
YCombinator on a mobile food app.

00:03:37.150 --> 00:03:39.340
But YC founder Paul Graham encouraged them

00:03:39.340 --> 00:03:42.160
to work on something else,
a startup that could serve

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:43.750
as the front page of the internet.

00:03:45.190 --> 00:03:47.380
You were in the inaugural
Y Combinator class?

00:03:47.380 --> 00:03:49.360
Yeah, 2005 with

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:51.730
21 years ago, almost
21 ago. 20 years ago.

00:03:51.730 --> 00:03:53.320
With Sam Altman.
It's a good crew.

00:03:53.320 --> 00:03:54.640
Steve Huffman, your co-founder at

00:03:54.640 --> 00:03:56.050
Reddit. That's the Twitch guys's

00:03:56.050 --> 00:03:57.050
Twitch guys.

00:03:57.050 --> 00:03:59.080
Justin and Emmett. In 2005,

00:03:59.080 --> 00:04:02.470
it was an eclectic group of
folks in that first YC batch.

00:04:02.470 --> 00:04:05.350
It was not normal to wanna
do a startup in 2005.

00:04:05.350 --> 00:04:06.880
And that was the genius of YC.

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:09.190
They realized this opportunity
before everyone else did.

00:04:09.190 --> 00:04:12.850
Let's give for us it was
$12,000 for two college kids

00:04:12.850 --> 00:04:14.200
to go build a company.

00:04:14.200 --> 00:04:15.310
Maybe it could one day be worth

00:04:15.310 --> 00:04:16.505
billions.

00:04:16.505 --> 00:04:18.640
You know, Sam is the one exception.

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:22.840
I think he had a roadmap to
what tech could be in the world.

00:04:22.840 --> 00:04:25.780
Speaking for myself, I was
just happy to not have a boss.

00:04:25.780 --> 00:04:28.870
I was just happy to, you
know, build something

00:04:28.870 --> 00:04:30.310
that I cared about every day and

00:04:30.310 --> 00:04:32.710
and build something that just seemed fun.

00:04:32.710 --> 00:04:33.940
This was just one year

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:37.150
after Mark Zuckerberg had
started "The Facebook" and one year

00:04:37.150 --> 00:04:39.490
before Twitter got off the ground,

00:04:39.490 --> 00:04:41.710
the internet was just starting
to wake up to the idea

00:04:41.710 --> 00:04:43.900
that users, not editors could be the

00:04:43.900 --> 00:04:45.820
driving force for content.

00:04:45.820 --> 00:04:48.970
Ohanian and Huffman's site
went all in on this concept,

00:04:48.970 --> 00:04:50.350
a site they named Reddit.

00:04:56.410 --> 00:04:58.120
The memes, the inside jokes,

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:01.540
the crowdsourced investigations,
even Snoo the mascot,

00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:03.700
which Ohanian drew himself would

00:05:03.700 --> 00:05:06.520
for many define internet
culture of that era.

00:05:07.540 --> 00:05:11.200
This is the zeitgeist for a
quarter of a billion people.

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:14.740
After a year of building
Reddit was courted by Conde Nast.

00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:18.580
Ohanian and Huffman sold for
a reported $10 million.

00:05:18.580 --> 00:05:20.860
Life-changing money for them at the time,

00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:22.990
but in hindsight, a pittance for a company

00:05:22.990 --> 00:05:26.320
that today is valued at
close to $35 billion.

00:05:27.550 --> 00:05:30.790
Ohanian went on to become
a partner at Y Combinator

00:05:30.790 --> 00:05:32.650
where he mentored startups

00:05:32.650 --> 00:05:36.430
and co-founded Initialized
Capital with Gary Tan, a firm

00:05:36.430 --> 00:05:39.310
that backed companies like
Instacart and Coinbase.

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:41.680
But Ohanian decided

00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:44.170
to go it alone starting
his own venture firm.

00:05:44.170 --> 00:05:47.980
776, named after the date
of the first Olympic Games.

00:05:49.810 --> 00:05:51.340
What's your snapshot on

00:05:51.340 --> 00:05:53.050
where venture capital is at the moment?

00:05:53.050 --> 00:05:55.720
It's been a really difficult environment.

00:05:55.720 --> 00:05:56.930
Yeah.
What's your take?

00:05:56.930 --> 00:06:00.290
There's a middle of
VC firms that are just,

00:06:00.290 --> 00:06:01.970
as the kids would say, "mid"

00:06:01.970 --> 00:06:04.820
That are probably
gonna have a really hard time

00:06:04.820 --> 00:06:07.970
because they can't get into
the deals that the, the biggest

00:06:07.970 --> 00:06:09.710
and baddest firms can, can easily get into

00:06:09.710 --> 00:06:11.330
and have the capital to get into.

00:06:11.330 --> 00:06:12.890
And I think you're in a business

00:06:12.890 --> 00:06:17.180
where there are these
outsized mega firms, right?

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:18.500
The Sequoias, the Andreessen's,

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:22.040
but also the sort of newer
generations, like the Thrives.

00:06:22.040 --> 00:06:24.200
And they will continue to get more

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:26.270
and more capital as they clearly are,

00:06:26.270 --> 00:06:28.070
you know, the big dogs with the war chest

00:06:28.070 --> 00:06:29.090
that can double down in those

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:30.320
big winners at the later stage.

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:32.360
And then at the early stage,
there are firms, I like

00:06:32.360 --> 00:06:34.010
to believe SevenSevenSix is one of them

00:06:34.010 --> 00:06:35.780
that can win against all comers

00:06:35.780 --> 00:06:37.280
and that have a clear value proposition

00:06:37.280 --> 00:06:38.990
and want to be the best. Early

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:43.310
Through SevenSevenSix Ohanian has
backed an eclectic portfolio,

00:06:43.310 --> 00:06:44.930
including companies like Doji,

00:06:44.930 --> 00:06:48.500
which lets users virtually
try on clothes, Mast,

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:51.530
a forest restoration company, Feastables

00:06:51.530 --> 00:06:52.363
the snack brand launched
by Jimmy Donaldson, AKA MrBeast,

00:06:52.363 --> 00:06:53.196
and Monumental Labs
where they're using robots

00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:00.470
to make stone construction scalable.

00:07:00.470 --> 00:07:02.720
Today Ohanian is capturing footage to post

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:04.850
to his social media followers.

00:07:04.850 --> 00:07:07.310
It's part of the SevenSevenSix playbook,

00:07:07.310 --> 00:07:09.320
capital plus megaphone.

00:07:11.275 --> 00:07:15.620
Boop. Ohanian made his most
famous VC bet five years

00:07:15.620 --> 00:07:17.150
ago in an asset class

00:07:17.150 --> 00:07:20.900
most of his peers had long
ignored women's sports.

00:07:26.780 --> 00:07:29.990
On Season 1 of The Circuit,
he told us how it came to pass

00:07:29.990 --> 00:07:31.100
In 2019,

00:07:31.100 --> 00:07:35.690
I drunkenly tweeted from
the Women's World Cup

00:07:35.690 --> 00:07:38.510
that women's soccer was
the most undervalued

00:07:38.510 --> 00:07:40.400
opportunity in sports.

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:42.290
And a bunch of people on Twitter
said, all right, you know

00:07:42.290 --> 00:07:44.480
what, Alexis, put your
money where your mouth is.

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:45.800
He went in with three partners

00:07:45.800 --> 00:07:47.510
to buy Angel City Football Club,

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:49.790
bringing capital from SevenSevenSix, along

00:07:49.790 --> 00:07:52.400
with additional investment from Serena.

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:56.060
What was your relationship to
women's sports before Serena?

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:59.420
Non-existent As a casual
American sports fan,

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:02.060
if you just ask us, you
know, close your eyes

00:08:02.060 --> 00:08:05.630
and think of American soccer
excellence, you can only think

00:08:05.630 --> 00:08:07.670
of women 'cause the men
have never been great.

00:08:07.670 --> 00:08:09.290
And so it all starts with the money.

00:08:09.290 --> 00:08:11.060
None of this, you're never
gonna hear me talking about the

00:08:11.060 --> 00:08:14.450
charity of it, the the
social issues, the feminism.

00:08:14.450 --> 00:08:16.700
No, no, no, no. This is excellence.

00:08:16.700 --> 00:08:21.200
This is the market rewarding
excellence and looking around.

00:08:21.200 --> 00:08:22.340
I just couldn't believe

00:08:22.340 --> 00:08:24.290
that these other sports soccer especially

00:08:24.290 --> 00:08:26.900
where there isn't a
strong male counterpart in

00:08:26.900 --> 00:08:28.970
America. Why there wasn't

00:08:28.970 --> 00:08:29.970
something.

00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:31.640
Yeah, just four years later,

00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:33.770
the club's value had soared from two

00:08:33.770 --> 00:08:37.340
to $250 million along the way.

00:08:37.340 --> 00:08:40.310
There were reports of infighting
over the team's direction.

00:08:40.310 --> 00:08:42.050
It was later bought by Disney CEO.

00:08:42.050 --> 00:08:44.390
Bob Iger and his wife Willow Bay

00:08:44.390 --> 00:08:47.960
and Ohanian moved on to
fund other sports ventures.

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:51.980
A UK women's soccer team, a
women's sports bar franchise,

00:08:51.980 --> 00:08:54.080
a team in Tiger Woods Golf League,

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:56.070
and a professional
women's volleyball team.

00:08:57.510 --> 00:09:01.920
And we haven't even gotten to
Athlos. What's Athlos? You say

00:09:03.265 --> 00:09:04.530
The the future of track and field.

00:09:04.530 --> 00:09:07.290
Really like a Formula 1 type
model. Building is a formula

00:09:07.290 --> 00:09:08.880
1 for track and field.

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:12.360
Let's build a formula
1 of track and field

00:09:12.360 --> 00:09:13.560
In case you miss that.

00:09:13.560 --> 00:09:16.680
Athlos is Ohanian's take on
Formula one meets track

00:09:16.680 --> 00:09:19.560
and field, part racing, part spectacle,

00:09:19.560 --> 00:09:20.610
and definitive proof

00:09:20.610 --> 00:09:24.300
that Alexis Ohanian's marketing
muscle is everything everywhere.

00:09:24.300 --> 00:09:27.630
All at once from a
launch party at Tiffany,

00:09:27.630 --> 00:09:29.850
which made sparkling
crowns for the winners

00:09:29.850 --> 00:09:33.270
to an electrifying long jump
qualifier in Times Square,

00:09:33.270 --> 00:09:35.460
featuring gold medalist
Tara Davis Woodhall

00:09:45.305 --> 00:09:48.630
to Randall's Island in New
York City where all roads lead

00:09:48.630 --> 00:09:50.730
to the second annual Athlos event.

00:09:50.730 --> 00:09:53.400
A track meet Ohanian
wants to take on the road

00:09:53.400 --> 00:09:56.670
and around the world. Women's
sports are having a moment.

00:09:56.670 --> 00:09:58.200
You know, we're seeing
what's happening with soccer.

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:00.870
The WNBA is having a moment,

00:10:00.870 --> 00:10:03.750
but also there's a lot of
controversy around these sports.

00:10:03.750 --> 00:10:06.750
And so there's a question
about what happens when you

00:10:06.750 --> 00:10:09.180
fast track a league to prominence.

00:10:09.180 --> 00:10:12.510
How do you have the correct leadership

00:10:12.510 --> 00:10:15.420
and the correct vision in
place to sustain that momentum?

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:18.780
Can you explain the
various revenue streams,

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:21.750
the broadcast rights, the
sponsorships, the merch,

00:10:21.750 --> 00:10:23.940
the ticket sales, the
athletes getting a cut.

00:10:23.940 --> 00:10:25.500
Yeah.
How does it all work together

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:27.570
and when does this become profitable?

00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:30.900
So for any emerging league,
those media deals you see

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:32.610
for the NFL, NBA, billions of dollars,

00:10:32.610 --> 00:10:33.960
that is a long ways away.

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:36.060
So we said from jump, we're not gonna try

00:10:36.060 --> 00:10:37.560
to make a little bit of revenue out

00:10:37.560 --> 00:10:39.180
of the gate for broadcast.

00:10:39.180 --> 00:10:40.650
I'd rather make no money

00:10:40.650 --> 00:10:42.030
and instead reach millions of people.

00:10:42.030 --> 00:10:43.950
So last year we made
no money on broadcast,

00:10:43.950 --> 00:10:45.780
but we reached 3 million viewers.

00:10:45.780 --> 00:10:48.390
'cause we were everywhere.
YouTube, X, DAZN

00:10:48.390 --> 00:10:50.640
ESPN Plus ESPN two.

00:10:50.640 --> 00:10:52.470
This year we actually added Ion.

00:10:52.470 --> 00:10:53.790
And then one of the important
things we did was we,

00:10:53.790 --> 00:10:56.820
we set the record for prize
money last year simply

00:10:56.820 --> 00:10:57.960
by doubling the top prize.

00:10:57.960 --> 00:11:00.690
It was only $30,000, we made it 60.

00:11:00.690 --> 00:11:02.880
And we wanna work in
concert with our athletes.

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:06.600
So 10% of all the revenue in
some from this event also goes

00:11:06.600 --> 00:11:08.250
into a pool that goes
to all those athletes.

00:11:08.250 --> 00:11:09.420
When you're buying
merch, when you're buying

00:11:09.420 --> 00:11:10.800
hot dogs, you're buying tickets.

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:12.450
That revenue comes together.

00:11:12.450 --> 00:11:14.310
When Athlos expands Next year,

00:11:14.310 --> 00:11:17.100
three top athletes will also have equity.

00:11:17.100 --> 00:11:18.270
Tara Davis Woodhall

00:11:18.270 --> 00:11:21.600
and sprinters Sha'Carri
Richardson and Gabby Thomas.

00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:24.930
And that means a voice in shaping athlos.

00:11:24.930 --> 00:11:27.510
When Alexis called you and
said he wanted to start Athlos,

00:11:27.510 --> 00:11:29.850
what did you say you wanted?
Like what was your advice?

00:11:29.850 --> 00:11:30.930
Well, he asked me, he is like,

00:11:30.930 --> 00:11:32.070
what do you want as an athlete?

00:11:32.070 --> 00:11:34.650
And I was like, I wanna see
that long jump meet as sexy

00:11:34.650 --> 00:11:35.670
as the a hundred meter dash.

00:11:35.670 --> 00:11:39.180
And he asked me, what's my dream?

00:11:39.180 --> 00:11:41.310
And I told him my dream is street meets.

00:11:41.310 --> 00:11:43.020
So I told him, you know,

00:11:43.020 --> 00:11:44.340
it would be cool to jump in Times Square.

00:11:44.340 --> 00:11:47.010
And he was like, Times Square?
And I said, Times Square.

00:11:47.010 --> 00:11:49.710
What does this event mean to
you being not just an athlete

